{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5fdebfb-26d5-4676-b32e-390fe83eb312","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID generation strategy** from `DisplayName` to `FullyQualifiedName`. Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so every test looks new.\n\n**Fix** — add a `.runsettings` file (or update your existing one) to restore the old strategy:\n\n```xml\n<RunSettings>\n  <MSTest>\n    <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n  </MSTest>\n</RunSettings>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it's no longer tied to a specific test. Accessing `TestName` throws because no individual test is running yet. In v3 it would silently return the name of whichever test triggered class init (unreliable anyway).\n\nYour code on **line 13** hits this:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix** — remove or guard that access. If you need per-test setup, move the logic to `[TestInitialize]` where `TestContext` is bound to a real test:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // works fine here\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` (float/double)** | Default tolerance is now **exact** (`0`). Tests using `Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` on floats may start failing. Pass an explicit delta. |\n| **Parallel execution** | v4 defaults to `ExecutionScope.ClassLevel` parallelism. If your tests assumed serial execution, add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or disable it. |\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Stricter type matching — e.g. passing `1` (int) to a `long` parameter may no longer auto-coerce. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Now read-only in some contexts; writes in `[ClassInitialize]` may throw. |\n| **Removed APIs** | `TestContext.DataConnection`, `TestContext.DataRow` (legacy data-driven) are removed. Use `[DynamicData]` or `[DataRow]` instead. |\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` to fix the `ClassInitialize` issue?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"544f8d37-168e-4eef-ae1a-92bb6fb0de33","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes. Let me also look at the specific code issue with `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes I know about:\n\n1. **Fully qualified test ID** — MSTest v4 changed the default test ID format to use fully qualified names (namespace + class + method). This means Azure DevOps sees them as completely new tests, losing history. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in `.runsettings` or project properties.\n\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — The `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now class-level rather than test-level, so `TestContext.TestName` no longer works since there's no specific test executing at that point—this differs from v3 where it would return the first test's name.\n3. Other notable changes include stricter floating-point comparisons in `Assert.AreEqual`, adjustments to `DeploymentItem` behavior, and modifications to how `DataRow` attributes function.\n4. Parallelization defaults and `TestContext.Properties` behavior have also shifted in v4.","outputTokens":1001,"requestId":"4C28:1BD058:1134EC4:14C898D:6A01473A"},"id":"a4d79c7a-75c2-4313-a20f-22a9fbc259ce","timestamp":"2026-05-11T03:04:48.202Z","parentId":"32e6e677-33db-4ae3-aa82-64bbe5007841"}
